						<summary>

						<p>The record belongs to the reign of <hi rend="bold">Amōghavarsha I</hi> and is <hi rend="bold">dated in Śaka 784, Chitrabhānu (= A.D. 862).</hi> It registers the gift of the village <hi rend="bold">Pipparage</hi> (<hi rend="italic">i.e.,</hi> modern Hūvina-Hippargi) situated in the <hi rend="bold">Kannavuri-vishaya</hi> to the astrologer Gōleya-Bhaṭṭa. The gift is stated to be a <hi rend="italic">Raṭṭa-maḻtaṇḍa (mārtaṇḍa)-datti,</hi><note n="4-3">This pillar was originally built into the platform on the out at the time of inspection.</note>thus supplying us with a hitherto unknown <hi rend="italic">biruda</hi> of the king, <hi rend="italic">viz.,</hi> <hi rend="bold">Raṭṭa-maḻtaṇḍa</hi> (<hi rend="bold">Raṭṭa-mārtaṇḍa</hi><note n="4-4">See p. 5, f. n. 1.</note>). </p>						

						</summary>
					</msContents>
